Turkey expands its diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey intended to be a member of the European Union, European powers nested the desire to penetrate the interior of this country.
In the eastern part of the Bosporus, perhaps just 20 steps inland, lies one of the most interesting relics of the disastrous imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha train station was designed by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu, in neo-Renaissance style.
At least, this is what the guides say.
The building is set at the end of the platforms and has two towers in front, one for each corner, resembling a typical German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The building in its complex is a bit decadent.
But once the locker was over, there’s no question what the greatness of the company was that this was the westernmost door.
The station was inaugurated in August 1908 by the German consortium Anatolia-Bagdad Corporation.
Germany, a "latecomer" in the imperial game, had the ambition to dominate the Middle East through this railroad that healed as far as Damascus, Baghdad, and beyond in what is now Saudi Arabia.
However, the ambitions of this imperial Germany failed during World War I.
Its railroads were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular Arabs.
Because of the relative isolation of the surrounding regions, generated by the frozen frontiers of the Cold War, it fell under
When the forces advanced into Egypt, they pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
The news was also bad for Hyderpasha station.
In 1917, a munitions train exploded, destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources said it was sabotage.
Since then the station has fallen apart and stayed out of history.
But today, this railway, the gateway to Anatolia and all the eastern centers, serves - at least symbolically - to highlight Turkey's willingness to broaden its diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party – the AKP – has planned a new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation of the surrounding regions, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
Now there is a new policy of collaboration.
The Turkish government maintains excellent relations with Israel and Syria, with both Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
To evaluate the parameters of this new foreign policy, I climbed to a bunk bed and went to the Turkish capital Ankara, in order to visit one of the leaders of the AKP, expert in foreign policy, the Turkish Prime Minister Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a trip of shakes, which produced the cadences of the ancient world in the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital - a new city, designed to govern a new secular state, far from the Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, with its clear Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
It has raised some suspicions in the West and especially in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern structure of stone and steel - built ad hoc - in a developing suburb, surrounded by half-built shopping malls and "power bakeries" where middle-class managers in business suits - men and women - meet early in the morning to agree/do business.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a center-right politician of almost any party in Europe.
Suit, tie, I'm sure he still has a Blackberry.
“The aim of the party’s foreign policy is to re-integrate Turkey into its immediate neighbourhood.
The Cold War was an anomaly,” he says.
Turkey has been cut off in relations with its interior.
Today you have to look at the East and the West at the same time.
It is not a case if it is not to one or the other.
You have to do both.
“But surely at some point,” I ask, “Could Turkey be forced to choose?”
“Turkey,” he replies, “does not want to face that choice.”
He then underlines a point that almost everyone I have spoken to has recited to me almost from memory: Turkey's relations not only with the Middle East, but with the Caucasus region, and with all the Black Sea, represent a benefit for Europe and the United States as well as for Turkey itself.
The message seems to be: with Turkey on board, Europe in its complex can metaphorically assemble those rail lines that open the world to East Asia and the Middle East.
Once again at Hydarpasha station, after a second sleepless night, my thoughts go back to the two German gentlemen, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who had attended the construction of this building 100 years ago.
How surprised would they have been to learn that Europe’s ambitions in the Middle East would, in large part, be in Turkey’s hands today?
And waiting at the terminal for the ferry that will take me back across the Bosporus, I remember that in those days Turkey was considered "the sick man of Europe."
So, there is not much doubt on which continent this fascinating country must claim.
