Morgan Stanley adopted this new statute last week, which would have to allow him to diversify his activities but he passes under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
Its alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis forces Wall Street’s biggest names to behave much more cautiously than before.
The modalities presented last Monday also show that the deal has been modified over the past few days: on Monday, Morgan had announced that he would sell up to 20% of his shares to Japanese for almost $8.5 billion.
“A week ago, Toshihide Mizuno, the chief executive of MUFG, explained in Tokyo, “we thought that the stake would have been composed only of ordinary shares.
But in view of the current economic and market situation, we wanted to minimize risks and cover ourselves.”
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley securities 7% below their book value.
And the transaction will result in a dilution of about 20% of the profit per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferred shares into ordinary shares within a year if they are sold at more than 50% above the conversion price, i.e. at $47 or so, over a given period.
Morgan Stanley says the capital provided by MUFG will allow it to seize investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
A spokeswoman for the group declined to elaborate on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
After MUFG’s investment, Morgan Stanley should show a Tier One solvency ratio of about 15%, one of the best in the industry.
Morgan said he had eased his balance sheet a lot since late August.
The past few weeks have been exhausting for the group, which saw its stock price fall by half as the cost of insurance against a risk of defaults on its debt took off.
This cost fell last Monday but remained at a high level, around 12%.
