Rafael Correa in Quito on Monday.
Refounding the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his colleagues and friends, he is the third to vote on a bill for a new constitution.
Mission accomplished as 64% of voters voted "yes" to the referendum, according to official results that referred to 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" obtained 28%, 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% were blank votes.
For the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to get half of the vote plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted out of polling stations and a count from a non-governmental organization had announced a broad “yes” victory, estimating it to be between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed on the night of Sunday to Monday the victory of his draft Constitution.
The “Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly,” he said, congratulating Ecuadorians who lead the Guayaquil government, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
Thus, Rafael Correa has been congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also by his Chilean colleague Micaela Bachelet.
The election, which will take place in full calm, according to the Organization of American States (OAS) observation mission, referred to a 444-point text that consolidated the "new socialism" defended by the president.
The draft Constitution entails increasing the power of the state over the economy, reserving it the “development planning” of a country that lives essentially thanks to the extraction of oil by foreign companies and thanks to currencies sent by its emigrants.
Led by Correa, elected in 2006, the draft also grants enhanced powers to the head of state, who may serve up to two consecutive terms of four years each and have the possibility of dissolving the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he would use this power and seek a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution also consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the President has begun to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, in which 50% of the population lives under the poverty line.
It finally provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for American anti-drug operations.
The 19 people kidnapped have been released in Chad.
An Egyptian commando launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions captured ten days ago.
They are in Cairo.
Eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions kidnapped 10 days ago in the desert arrived unharmed in the Egyptian capital after being released on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been released by Egyptian special forces in Chad.
They all looked good upon arrival at 3:30 p.m. aboard a special aircraft at the Al Maza military base, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
Helicopters immediately transported them to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for medical testing, so they have not been able to speak to the press.
"They are in good health" and "no ransom was paid" to the hijackers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garana said at the airport.
On September 19, these hostages fell into the hands of 35 unknown kidnappers while enjoying an off-road safari in a desert area at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, and have since passed from one azule to another.
The group consisted of eleven tourists – five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian – and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the travel agency Aegyptus, in charge of the organization of the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, transported aboard two helicopters, had launched the assault overnight before dawn.
"An exchange of gunfire occurred, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others have fled," said the official, who kept the anonymous.
According to him, 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "blitz" unit were sent to Sudan, where they had the support of German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini mentioned in Belgrade the role played by secret agents and members of Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our secret service men, of the special forces," he said without going into details.
He also denied payment of a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted during a patrol an off-roader on board which were the kidnappers, of whom killed six, including the Chadian chief and arrested two.
He also claimed that they were related to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), a claim immediately denied by this group.
Letters - Silent Majority of Culture
A debate on the financing of culture makes headlines and occupies the current electoral campaign.
Better like that.
But a part of our cultural life is always forgotten.
Who will stand up to denounce the miserable sums granted to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or starving national historic sites?
Which politician will dare to remind the federal government to neglect its monuments and heritage buildings?
Why don’t we have real laws that actually preserve our heritage as in Canada and Quebec?
Did you know that the French government spends three and a half million euros to restore only the Château de Chinon in the Loire Valley?
In the United States, it is written in its Constitution that the protection of heritage is part of the culture of Americans and that this heritage must be protected by all citizens, all elected officials and all government departments, and all this, in concert.
In Quebec, in the Federation of Quebec Historical Societies, at least 40,000 benevolent people regrouped in 211 societies of history, heritage, archives and genealogy are concerned with searching history, preserving piles of private archives for little money, and preserving archaeological remains.
These are often the watchdogs of our heritage, who protest with energy and desperation when promoters and leaders throw their bulldozers at our old stones and our forgotten cemeteries.
When, a monument to history and heritage?
The governments of the Netherlands nationalize a part of Fortis Bank.
The Netherlands - being the first in Europe - will help with a nationalization of the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis that is in trouble due to the effect of the mortgage crisis of the North American market: the three countries will support in total with 11.2 billion euros to this financial and insurance institution that also has business in Hungary.
This weekend the governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held higher-level consultations with the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commission’s head of economic competition.
The Fortis Bank is the first to have suffered the crisis of the Eurozone in the context of the international financial crisis that has been occurring in several waves more than a year ago, therefore the decisions taken regarding the Bank can in a sense be considered as precedents.
According to the decision made in the early hours of Sunday, the three states will buy about half (49 percent) of the property owned by the Bank in their area.
The bank will certainly sell a portion of its business, including mostly insurance activities purchased last year from the Dutch ABN Amró.
The actions of Fortis began a sharp decline last week and by the second half of the week there were already important signs of crisis at the institution.
Analysts agree, however, that with its 85,000 employees this bank is too big to allow it to break down.
Shares in the company fell 12 percent on Friday alone, the lowest point in 14 years.
Since January, the value of the shares has declined by more than two-thirds.
Looking at current stock prices, the total value of the group’s capital in the market is around 14 billion euros, but according to the company’s executives this is not real.
The Bank’s management blamed the sharp drop in Fortis shares on the insecurities of the U.S. market in connection with the approval of the $700 billion U.S. package plan.
On Monday, stocks showed a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the bank’s new CEO.
The bank also sought private investors, but so far no one has given a concrete offer.
The Belgian government had previously assured that investors did not have to worry, they will not lose their money.
Among the Bank’s clients so far there was no panic, they did not invade the bank offices to withdraw their money.
Fortis has its own branch in Hungary and has also purchased leasing companies.
Fox in the chicken coop
In the U.S., life and health insurance companies when viewing drug purchase data often deny signing an insurance contract.
Privacy policy specialists fear that the market for personal data will become uncontrollable.
“There are personal data protection programs, which combine the use of recipe data in all cases with the approval of the given person.
The same should be in independent hands, because if not, "we entrust the chicken to the fox" - quotes the Washington Post to Richard Dick, designer of the prescription tracking program.
Insurance companies rely on the price of insurance and the amount of compensation from the client’s health status and if they believe the risk is excessive, they simply don’t make the contract.
Before, they sent the client to medical check-up and signed the contract with him, already knowing the result of the check-up.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: with the customer identification number he easily gets from pharmacies the list of drugs purchased in the last year and a half and the program itself draws the conclusion about the illness and health of the customer.
For example, if you systematically take large doses of cholesterol-lowering pills, it indicates that your blood fat level is virtually incurably high, so you are immediately included in a higher risk category.
Numerous versions of the program circulate, some even establish a number of risks, so the insurance company in addition to the administration has little to do, although there are small difficulties in this regard.
Among the disadvantages of the program is for example that some drugs are multipurpose, for example certain substances serve both to treat headaches and for heat waves and even as antidepressants.
The latter is a major risk-increasing factor for insurance companies while the former are not.
Special companies were formed to consult and process this data, which before acquiring the necessary information from pharmacies, ask for the approval of the patient.
The authorities are already forcing them to do so, although they have not received a fine for negligence so far.
Some companies have recently also developed the results of laboratory tests and by combining them with drug consumption data they obtain more accurate information about the patient’s health status.
More and more companies have access to this data and at the same time it is becoming increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is an exclusive law for the protection of personal health data, but it applies only to insurance companies and those that provide health services.
The bill that entitles the authority to control specialized companies for the provision of personal data is already before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is insufficient: therefore he developed his program, which will require the specific approval of the person for the provision of his own personal data.
It is another matter that such a person cannot deny his approval, because otherwise the insurance companies will not sign the contract with him.
So the hens, in spite of everything, are exposed to the goodwill of the fox.
Global menu of Marseille
EU doubles trade with India
As the European Union and India are reciprocal trading partners, this issue in addition to the other mostly global issues dominated the agenda of the ninth summit.
A Franco-Indian summit will also be held today, to deal mainly with cooperation in nuclear energy.
Although the European Union recognizes that India is a major developing democratic power that should have more voice and vote in international affairs, member countries have not yet been able to reach a common denominator on whether they should support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
This issue was not addressed at the ninth summit that began yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, EU President, Commission President José Manuel Barroso and Javier Solana, the main foreign policy representative, welcomed Manmohan Singh, Prime Minister of India, with whom they reached an agreement to double in five years, i.e. increase their trade to more than one hundred billion euros.
Considering that between the years 2000 and 2007 the exchange of goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not an excessively ambitious goal.
They have thus legally harmonised the twenty-six existing bilateral civil aviation agreements with India, so that air transport will also be able to fly in the future.
India wants to sign a free trade agreement with the EU until the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up negotiations.
The goal is balance, because while the EU is India’s first trading partner, New Delhi only ranks ninth among the Union’s trading partners.
The summit paid attention to global issues.
Both sides condemned the Afghan and Pakistani situation and terrorism - all forms of the latter - and urged the convening of a UN conference.
The conclusion of the Doha trade liberalization round was also urged, although both sides have great responsibility for its failure.
The EU has confirmed that it will stick to its energy and climate programme, that is, by 2020 it wants to reduce polluting emissions by at least 20%.
India also agrees with this, as at next year’s climate conference a global agreement should be reached and production of greenhouse gases should decrease by 50 percent by 2050.
They also wanted to hamper the rise in food prices and supported the convening of an international conference to review the financial crisis.
Today the head of government of India will travel to the French capital, where - in a bilateral meeting - he will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy.
Paris is confident that French companies will receive orders worth 20 billion euros to build nuclear reactors.
According to news agency information the agreement would be for a period of 15 years.
